Energy Pack Ingestion and Threshold Detection
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line proficiency
Understanding of system metrics and monitoring concepts
Familiarity with text editors (nano or vim)
Basic knowledge of configuration files and log analysis
Understanding of alerting concepts
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Ingest and monitor energy consumption metrics from system data
Configure threshold-based detection rules
Generate automated alerts when thresholds are exceeded
Implement a complete monitoring pipeline using open-source tools
Environment Setup
You will use the bare-metal Linux machine provided through the "Start Lab" button. All tools will be installed during this lab.

Required Tools
Telegraf: Metrics collection agent
InfluxDB: Time-series database for storing metrics
Kapacitor: Real-time streaming data processing engine for threshold detection and alerting
Task 1: Install and Configure the Monitoring Stack
Step 1.1: Install InfluxDB
# Download and install InfluxDB
wget https://dl.influxdata.com/influxdb/releases/influxdb2-2.7.4-amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i influxdb2-2.7.4-amd64.deb

# Start InfluxDB service
sudo systemctl start influxdb
sudo systemctl enable influxdb
Step 1.2: Initialize InfluxDB
# Setup InfluxDB (use default port 8086)
influx setup \
  --username admin \
  --password adminpassword123 \
  --org energyorg \
  --bucket energy_metrics \
  --retention 168h \
  --force
Save the API token displayed after setup - you'll need it later.

Step 1.3: Install Telegraf
# Download and install Telegraf
wget https://dl.influxdata.com/telegraf/releases/telegraf_1.29.1-1_amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i telegraf_1.29.1-1_amd64.deb
Step 1.4: Configure Telegraf for Energy Metrics Collection
Create a custom Telegraf configuration:

sudo nano /etc/telegraf/telegraf.conf
Replace the contents with this configuration template:

[agent]
  interval = "10s"
  round_interval = true
  metric_batch_size = 1000
  metric_buffer_limit = 10000
  collection_jitter = "0s"
  flush_interval = "10s"
  flush_jitter = "0s"

[[outputs.influxdb_v2]]
  urls = ["http://localhost:8086"]
  token = "YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE"
  organization = "energyorg"
  bucket = "energy_metrics"

# CPU metrics as energy proxy
[[inputs.cpu]]
  percpu = true
  totalcpu = true
  collect_cpu_time = false
  report_active = true

# Memory metrics
[[inputs.mem]]

# Disk I/O metrics
[[inputs.diskio]]

# System load
[[inputs.system]]

# Custom energy simulation input
[[inputs.file]]
  files = ["/var/log/energy_data.log"]
  data_format = "influx"
  name_override = "energy_consumption"
TODO: Replace YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE with your actual InfluxDB API token from Step 1.2.

Step 1.5: Create Simulated Energy Data Source
Create a script to generate simulated energy consumption data:

sudo nano /usr/local/bin/energy_simulator.sh
Add the following script:

#!/bin/bash

LOG_FILE="/var/log/energy_data.log"
sudo touch $LOG_FILE
sudo chmod 666 $LOG_FILE

while true; do
    # TODO: Implement energy metric generation
    # Generate random power consumption between 50-150 watts
    POWER_WATTS=$((50 + RANDOM % 100))
    
    # Generate random voltage between 110-125V
    VOLTAGE=$((110 + RANDOM % 15))
    
    # Calculate current (I = P/V)
    CURRENT=$(echo "scale=2; $POWER_WATTS / $VOLTAGE" | bc)
    
    # TODO: Format as InfluxDB line protocol
    # Format: measurement,tag=value field=value timestamp
    TIMESTAMP=$(date +%s%N)
    echo "energy_consumption,location=datacenter,rack=A1 power_watts=${POWER_WATTS}i,voltage=${VOLTAGE}i,current=${CURRENT} ${TIMESTAMP}" >> $LOG_FILE
    
    sleep 5
done
Make it executable and run in background:

sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/energy_simulator.sh
nohup sudo /usr/local/bin/energy_simulator.sh > /dev/null 2>&1 &
Step 1.6: Start Telegraf
sudo systemctl start telegraf
sudo systemctl enable telegraf

# Verify Telegraf is running
sudo systemctl status telegraf
Step 1.7: Verify Data Ingestion
# Query InfluxDB to confirm data is being ingested
influx query 'from(bucket: "energy_metrics") 
  |> range(start: -5m) 
  |> filter(fn: (r) => r._measurement == "energy_consumption")
  |> limit(n: 10)' \
  --org energyorg \
  --token YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE
Expected Output: You should see recent energy consumption records with power_watts, voltage, and current fields.

Task 2: Configure Threshold Detection and Alerting
Step 2.1: Install Kapacitor
# Download and install Kapacitor
wget https://dl.influxdata.com/kapacitor/releases/kapacitor_1.7.0_amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i kapacitor_1.7.0_amd64.deb
Step 2.2: Configure Kapacitor
Edit Kapacitor configuration:

sudo nano /etc/kapacitor/kapacitor.conf
Update the InfluxDB section:

[[influxdb]]
  enabled = true
  name = "energydb"
  urls = ["http://localhost:8086"]
  token = "YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE"
  organization = "energyorg"
  default = true
Start Kapacitor:

sudo systemctl start kapacitor
sudo systemctl enable kapacitor
sudo systemctl status kapacitor
Step 2.3: Create Threshold Detection Script
Create a TICKscript for threshold-based alerting:

nano ~/energy_threshold_alert.tick
Add the following TICKscript template:

// TODO: Define the data stream from InfluxDB
stream
    |from()
        .measurement('energy_consumption')
        .groupBy('location', 'rack')
    // TODO: Create a time window for analysis
    |window()
        .period(30s)
        .every(10s)
    // TODO: Calculate mean power consumption
    |mean('power_watts')
        .as('avg_power')
    // TODO: Define alert condition - trigger when average power > 120 watts
    |alert()
        .id('energy-threshold-alert')
        .message('High energy consumption detected: {{ .Level }} - Average Power: {{ index .Fields "avg_power" }} watts in {{ index .Tags "location" }}/{{ index .Tags "rack" }}')
        .warn(lambda: "avg_power" > 100)
        .crit(lambda: "avg_power" > 120)
        // TODO: Configure alert output to log file
        .log('/var/log/kapacitor/energy_alerts.log')
Student Task: Complete the TICKscript by filling in the correct parameters:

Set the database and retention policy in from()
Configure appropriate window period
Verify threshold values match your requirements
Step 2.4: Define and Enable the Alert Task
# Define the task in Kapacitor
kapacitor define energy_alert \
  -tick ~/energy_threshold_alert.tick \
  -type stream \
  -dbrp energyorg.autogen

# Enable the task
kapacitor enable energy_alert

# Verify task is running
kapacitor show energy_alert
Step 2.5: Create Alert Log Directory
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/kapacitor
sudo chown kapacitor:kapacitor /var/log/kapacitor
sudo systemctl restart kapacitor
Step 2.6: Trigger Test Alerts
Modify the energy simulator to generate high consumption values:

# Temporarily generate high power values
for i in {1..10}; do
    TIMESTAMP=$(date +%s%N)
    echo "energy_consumption,location=datacenter,rack=A1 power_watts=135i,voltage=120i,current=1.125 ${TIMESTAMP}" | sudo tee -a /var/log/energy_data.log
    sleep 2
done
Step 2.7: Monitor Alerts
# Watch the alert log in real-time
tail -f /var/log/kapacitor/energy_alerts.log

# Check Kapacitor task statistics
kapacitor stats general

# List recent alerts
kapacitor list tasks
