Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Telegraf not collecting data

Check configuration syntax: telegraf --config /etc/telegraf/telegraf.conf --test
Verify API token is correct
Check file permissions on /var/log/energy_data.log
Issue: No alerts generated

Verify thresholds are being exceeded: Check actual power values in InfluxDB
Review Kapacitor logs: sudo journalctl -u kapacitor -n 100
Test TICKscript syntax: kapacitor show energy_alert
Issue: InfluxDB connection errors

Confirm InfluxDB is running: sudo systemctl status influxdb
Verify port 8086 is listening: sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 8086
Check token permissions in InfluxDB UI: http://localhost:8086
Conclusion
You have successfully implemented a complete energy monitoring pipeline with threshold-based alerting. This lab demonstrated:

Data Ingestion: Configured Telegraf to collect and forward energy metrics to InfluxDB
Threshold Detection: Implemented real-time monitoring using Kapacitor with configurable warning and critical thresholds
Alert Generation: Created automated alerts that trigger when energy consumption exceeds defined limits
This architecture is commonly used in DevOps environments for monitoring infrastructure health, resource utilization, and cost management. The skills learned apply directly to production monitoring systems, SRE practices, and observability platforms used in modern cloud-native applications.

Key Takeaways:

Time-series databases are optimal for metric storage and analysis
Stream processing enables real-time threshold detection
Proper alerting prevents resource waste and identifies anomalies early
The TICK stack (Telegraf, InfluxDB, Chronograf, Kapacitor) provides a complete open-source monitoring solution
